  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Unity.TextMeshPro::TMPro.TextMeshProUGUI
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "The artifact in the image is a commemorative brass head of a Queen Mother
    (Iyoba) from the historical Kingdom of Benin (located in present-day Nigeria).\n\nThe
    Legend of Queen Idia\nThis specific type of artifact represents Queen Idia, the
    mother of Oba Esigie, who ruled the Benin Kingdom in the early 16th century.\n\nA
    Warrior Queen: Idia is legendary for her military and political prowess. She
    raised her own army to help her son win critical battles against his rivals and
    the neighboring Igala kingdom.\n\nThe First Iyoba: To honor her essential role
    in his success, Oba Esigie created the title of Iyoba (Queen Mother) specifically
    for her. This gave her significant political power and her own palace.\n\nSymbolism
    and Design\nThe features of this bust are deeply symbolic of the Queen Mother's
    status:\n\nThe \"Parrot\u2019s Beak\" Crown: The distinctive high, forward-pointing
    conical crown is known as an ukpe-okhue. It is made of a lattice of coral beads,
    a material that symbolized wealth, power, and a connection to the sea deity Olokun.\n\nScarification:
    The four marks above each eye are gender-specific and represent her strength
    and military experience.\n\nAncestral Altars: These heads were commissioned by
    the reigning Oba to be placed on ancestral altars in the Queen Mother\u2019s
    residence or the royal palace. They served as focal points for communicating
    with the spirits of past rulers.\n\nHistorical Context and Restitution\nThe 1897
    Invasion: Thousands of these artifacts, collectively known as the Benin Bronzes,
    were looted from Benin City by British forces during a \"punitive expedition\"
    in 1897.\n\nGlobal Presence: Many of the original 16th-century brass heads are
    now held in major museums, including the British Museum in London, the Metropolitan
    Museum of Art in New York, and the Ethnological Museum of Berlin.\n\nModern Significance:
    These artifacts remain central to modern discussions about repatriation and the
    return of cultural heritage to Nigeria."
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
