--- !u!114 &6978355629502673217
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 914992003880463505}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 29b480dc3b7c34901916c4e135caebb1, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ArtifactController
  artifactData:
    description: "The artifact in the image is a commemorative brass head of a Queen
      Mother (Iyoba) from the historical Kingdom of Benin (located in present-day
      Nigeria).\n\nThe Legend of Queen Idia\nThis specific type of artifact represents
      Queen Idia, the mother of Oba Esigie, who ruled the Benin Kingdom in the early
      16th century.\n\nA Warrior Queen: Idia is legendary for her military and political
      prowess. She raised her own army to help her son win critical battles against
      his rivals and the neighboring Igala kingdom.\n\nThe First Iyoba: To honor
      her essential role in his success, Oba Esigie created the title of Iyoba (Queen
      Mother) specifically for her. This gave her significant political power and
      her own palace.\n\nSymbolism and Design\nThe features of this bust are deeply
      symbolic of the Queen Mother's status:\n\nThe \"Parrot\u2019s Beak\" Crown:
      The distinctive high, forward-pointing conical crown is known as an ukpe-okhue.
      It is made of a lattice of coral beads, a material that symbolized wealth,
      power, and a connection to the sea deity Olokun.\n\nScarification: The four
      marks above each eye are gender-specific and represent her strength and military
      experience.\n\nAncestral Altars: These heads were commissioned by the reigning
      Oba to be placed on ancestral altars in the Queen Mother\u2019s residence or
      the royal palace. They served as focal points for communicating with the spirits
      of past rulers.\n\nHistorical Context and Restitution\nThe 1897 Invasion: Thousands
      of these artifacts, collectively known as the Benin Bronzes, were looted from
      Benin City by British forces during a \"punitive expedition\" in 1897.\n\nGlobal
      Presence: Many of the original 16th-century brass heads are now held in major
      museums, including the British Museum in London, the Metropolitan Museum of
      Art in New York, and the Ethnological Museum of Berlin.\n\nModern Significance:
      These artifacts remain central to modern discussions about repatriation and
      the return of cultural heritage to Nigeria."
